<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>http://www</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h5 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by David Holland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold"> (IPC0027)</span></h5><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></h3><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Only question 9 of the Committee’s terms of reference is addressed here, namely:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Is the IPCC process an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">effective mechanism for assessing scientific knowledge?  Or has it focussed on providing a justification for political commitment?”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Publicly available evidence is described, showing that the IPCC process has always been over presumptive of the scientific k</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nowledge and has failed to ensure that the experts, who serve it, meet the required professional and ethical standards.   The IPCC has conspicuously failed to ensure any compliance with its fundamental principle of requiring a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“comprehensive, objective, op</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">en and transparent”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> process.   </span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given, the views already formed by the majority of its founders and their lack of any enforcement of its Principles</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Procedures</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the IPCC is seen by many as established to provide a justification for political commitmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t.   For these reasons it has never been fit for purpose.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The Foundation</span></h3><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bert Bolin a Professor of Meteorology was elected as the IPCC’s chairman at its 1988 inaugural session.   Of the 31 government delegations 19 made opening statements.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   Only the Isra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elis cautioned against over presumption:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“  ..  ..   before we cry "Wolf, wolf", we should have some scientific basis for the cry.  ..  ..  ..”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The United Kingdom’s presumptions were clear:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“United Kingdom welcomes this initiative as an important step towa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rds international consensus.   The United Kingdom government has long expressed its concern about the increase in greenhouse gases. We are committed to action based on sound scientific evidence but the UK believes some action is already justified.  ..  ” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rupert Darwall in his book, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘The Age of Global Warming’,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has charted the political events, people and environmental movements which led to the establishment of the IPCC.   Discussing Karl Popper’s view of science, Darwell remarks:</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Science advances throu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">gh challenge but maintaining the consensus subverts the needs of genuine scientific enquiry.   Politicisation of climate science and the de-legitimisation of debate – risks inherent in the idea of global warming – led to a retreat from the standards that e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">merged during the Scientific Revolution of the seventeenth century to pre-scientific norms; principally, reliance on consensus, peer review and appeals to authority.</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">University of East Anglia (UEA) Scientists have always played a leading role in the IPCC. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  In the ‘Climategate’ affair</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of 2009, over 1000 of their emails appeared on the Internet.   They exposed non-conformance with freedom of information law, which led to more demands for information and further disclosures.   Overall these show the need for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the IPCC process to be radically reformed or scrapped. </span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The FAR</span></h3><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sir John Houghton, the Director or Chief Executive of the Met Office (MO) from 1983 to 1991, was the UK’s ‘principal delegate’ at the IPCC session.   He was chosen to be the Chairman of IPCC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Working Group One (WGI), assessing the science, and the MO was to provide the Technical Support Unit (TSU).   The 1990 WGI IPCC First Assessment Report (FAR) was produced in draft form in just months, building on the 1986 work of SCOPE 29,</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which had been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">edited by Bolin and others.   Of its 22 contributors, 9 were from the UK, 5 of whom were from the UEA.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As with subsequent Reports, the FAR includes a Summary for PolicyMakers (SPM) which exudes confidence in the alarming predictions of climate models while</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ignoring fundamental scientific problems in attributing any impact of humans on global temperatures.   The Report itself, however, had reached conclusions which, in any other field of science, would have precluded confident predictions in its summary.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> global warming of larger size has almost certainly occurred at least once since the end of the last glaciation without any appreciable increase in greenhouse gases.   Because we do not understand the reasons for these past warming events it is not yet pos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">sible to attribute a specific proportion of the recent, smaller, warming to an increase of greenhouse gases.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Without certainty that late 20th century temperatures and CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> concentrations are exceptional in this current interglacial period, no rational pers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on should conclude that CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has played a sufficient part in the warming to justify the hugely expensive ‘decarbonisation’ of our economy and lifestyles.</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Houghton immediately began work on the 1992 Supplementary Report,</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> produced to support the negotiations for the Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   The report began the tradition of claiming increased confidence in the theories and computer models.   It also began a retreat from the FAR conclusions, rever</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sing the accepted null hypothesis:</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“It is still not possible to attribute with high confidence all, or even a large part of, the observed global warming to the enhanced greenhouse effect.   On the other hand, it is not possible to refute the claim that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">greenhouse-gas-induced climate change has contributed substantially to the observed warming.”</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 1992 most governments signed the UNFCCC.   Later, the IPCC’s ‘Principles’ were revised to require it to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“concentrate its activities”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  ..  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“on actions in suppor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">t of the” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UNFCCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   The clear presumption of the UNFCCC, in its article 2,</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that some particular concentration CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will adversely change the climate, inhibits the IPCC from pursuing actions which might conflict with the objective of curbing CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> emissions.</span></li></ol><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The SAR</span></h3><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">WGI for the 1995 IPCC Second Assessment Report (SAR)</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was also chaired by Houghton and the MO provided the TSU.   Entitled </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Is the 20th Century Warming Unusual?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” section 3.6 of Chapter 3 addressed the problem of the consensus on historic global te</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mperature.   The chapter concluded, that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of warming was unusual,</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but included ice core evidence in its Figure 3.22 which shows that temperature itself was not unusual.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The SAR became controversial</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> because important caveats on the certainty of mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">del predictions were deleted after the expert review stage, and citations of new literature unavailable to reviewers, were added to enable its SPM to be changed to state:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Nevertheless, the balance of evidence suggests that there is a discernible human inf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">luence on global climate.”</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The SAR exposed the influence of government officials on the reports.   Hundreds of IPCC appointed experts follow a review process to arrive at an agreed expert report and their SPM.   Subsequently, in late night sessions, as occ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">urred recently in Stockholm, a small sleep deprived group of the experts negotiated with the government officials to produce a final version of the SPM.   The underlying peer-reviewed experts’ report was then, without reference to the designated reviewers,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> edited to be consistent with what government officials insisted upon being stated in the SPM.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">This, now routine practice, totally invalidates any claim that IPCC Reports are peer-reviewed and suitable to inform policy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Political pressure was put upon t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he IPCC SAR process.   It has been reported</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that Houghton had received a letter from the US State Department stating:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“It is essential that the chapters not be finalized prior to the completion of the discussions at the IPCC Working Group I plenary in Mad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rid, and that chapter authors be prevailed upon to modify their text in an appropriate manner following the discussion in Madrid.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In his 2008 essay</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on the SAR, Houghton made clear that if what he thought to be the correct science had . . . .</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“not come th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rough unscathed, the integrity of the panel would have been seriously questioned, and governments would have faltered on taking urgent action on climate change, such as the signing in 1997 of the Kyoto Protocol.”</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The TAR</span></h3><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The SAR and the Kyoto Protocol were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> hard to follow.   The 2001 IPCC Third Assessment Report (TAR) had to settle the issue of whether current warming was exceptional.   Unless it is, no scientific certainty can be attached to attribution studies claiming CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> emissions to be its predominant c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ause.   David Deming would later report</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that after the SAR he was emailed by a climate scientists who stated,</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">"We have to get rid of the Medieval Warm Period."</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Fred Pearce</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> also revealed that from 1996 the hunt was on for a ‘hockey stick’.   This suggests</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that a group of IPCC contributors were “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">focussed on providing a justification for political commitment.”</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Again, Houghton chaired WGI for the TAR and the MO provided its TSU.   From the public’s point of view any possibility that the Medieval Warm Period w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as as warm as now with much lower concentrations of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> diminishes credibility in alarming predictions.   In 1996 Lloyd Keigwin had published a peer-reviewed proxy study of Sargasso Sea temperatures for 3,000 years supporting the FAR conclusions of earlier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> significantly warmer and cooler periods differing by up to 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">°</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C.</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   However, in 1999 a young ‘post doc’ IPCC Lead Author, Michael Mann, published a study with its much publicised graph looking like a ‘hockey stick’ by which it is now referred.</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   By claimi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng no more than 0.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">°</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C centennial temperature variation occurred before the industrial era, it contradicted the consensus of the FAR as well as Keigwin’s paper and borehole studies.</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The proxy data used in the ‘hockey stick’ and other studies, relied </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">upon by the IPCC to overturn the FAR consensus on historic temperatures, did not extend beyond 1980 to the late 20th century which the IPCC claim to be exceptionally warm.   Worse still, it was known that some of the proxy data wrongly indicated declining </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">temperature after 1960.    Climategate shows that the ‘hockey stick’ was disputed at the time by some who were well informed.</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   A small group of scientists agreed to “hide the decline” problem in another of the cited studies</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> without mentioning it in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">IPCC text, or even informing all the chapter’s Lead Authors.   One of them, Dr John Christy, told a US Congressional Committee:</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Regarding the Hockey Stick of IPCC 2001 evidence now indicates, in my view, that an IPCC Lead Author working with a small coho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rt of scientists, misrepresented the temperature record of the past 1000 years by (a) promoting his own result as the best estimate, (b) neglecting studies that contradicted his, and (c) amputating another’s result so as to eliminate conflicting data and l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">imit any serious attempt to expose the real uncertainties of these data.”</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ‘hockey stick’ was referenced as validating the low natural variability of the MO Hadley Centre climate model.</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   The hindcasting of 20th century temperatures</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was enabled by ass</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uming the low natural ‘unforced’ variability of the ‘hockey stick’ and arbitrarily chosen aerosols</span><a name="_ftnref29"></a><a href="#_ftn29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to account for the mid century cooling.   Lower assumptions on aerosols show a much less alarming sensitivity of the climate to CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref30"></a><a href="#_ftn30">[30]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The 2001 TAR and its ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hockey stick’ was presented</span><a name="_ftnref31"></a><a href="#_ftn31">[31]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by Houghton as proof of human induced climate change.   In 2002, extolling the qualities of the TAR, he wrote</span><a name="_ftnref32"></a><a href="#_ftn32">[32]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that all parts of any assessment process that form an input to policy making needed to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“completely open and trans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">parent”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and that,</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“IPCC documents including early drafts and review comments have been freely and widely available - adding much to the credibility of the process and its conclusions.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This was untrue.   Only eight boxes of unindexed papers were available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by appointment at Harvard.</span><a name="_ftnref33"></a><a href="#_ftn33">[33]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   A 2009 request to the MO for the TAR documents in their electronic form was refused on spurious grounds.</span><a name="_ftnref34"></a><a href="#_ftn34">[34]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   A new request resulted in the release of some of them on 21 November 2013.</span><a name="_ftnref35"></a><a href="#_ftn35">[35]</a></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">AR4</span></h3><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The 2007 IPCC WGI Fourth Assessment R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eport (AR4), was the first not chaired by Houghton nor technically supported by the MO.   It faced scrutiny from a public increasingly educated in science, the Internet, and the FOIA, as well as from opponents in the US Congress.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ‘hockey stick’s author</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was unhelpful to those who wanted to test its validity.</span><a name="_ftnref36"></a><a href="#_ftn36">[36]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   That the IPCC process should rely upon unverified studies with incomplete archiving reinforces its lack of fitness for purpose.   In 2003 Steve McIntyre and Ross McKitrick (MM) published a peer-re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">viewed paper which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">showed the ‘hockey stick’ to be wrong.</span><a name="_ftnref37"></a><a href="#_ftn37">[37]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   This was followed by further papers in 2005 after more information was revealed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2005 a House of Lords Select Committee on Economic Affairs commenced an enquiry into ‘The Economics of Climate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Change’ in which it took evidence</span><a name="_ftnref38"></a><a href="#_ftn38">[38]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on the science and economics from professional and lay people both supportive and critical of the IPCC process.   Asked (Q266) by Lord Macdonald about political pressures Professor Richard Tol stated, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Essentially in Germ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">any, for working groups 2 and 3—only people with close connections to the Green Party have been nominated to the IPCC, and that excludes me immediately.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Published in July 2005, the Committee’s Report</span><a name="_ftnref39"></a><a href="#_ftn39">[39]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> made the point (page 16) that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“… it is a concern that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the IPCC has not always sought to ensure that dissenting voices are given a full hearing”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  On page 29 they pointed to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“weaknesses in the way the scientific community, and the IPCC in particular, treats the impacts of climate change.   We call for a more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">balanced approach”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; and on page 56 they said that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“the IPCC’s procedures are not as open as they should be”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.   It also concluded on page 73 that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Sound science can not emerge from an unsound process.”</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Houghton was still active in promoting the ‘hockey stic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">k’ and addressed a US Senate Committee in July 2005,</span><a name="_ftnref40"></a><a href="#_ftn40">[40]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> stating that Eugene Wahl and Caspar Ammann (WA) had papers ‘in review’ and ‘in press’ that showed MM to be wrong.   In fact no paper was genuinely ‘in press’ nor any final pre-print available before the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> end of the final AR4 expert review stage.</span><a name="_ftnref41"></a><a href="#_ftn41">[41]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   The methodology of the only disputed matter in WA’s papers was never seen by the IPCC expert reviewers and only published a year after the release of AR4.</span><a name="_ftnref42"></a><a href="#_ftn42">[42]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Earlier, in June 2005 the new WGI TSU, then in the USA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, had laid down a firm ‘in press’ deadline of 16 December 2005</span><a name="_ftnref43"></a><a href="#_ftn43">[43]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> making it clear that all references to unpublished literature that did not meet that deadline would be removed from the drafts.   The Climategate emails show that, in February 2006, Wahl had l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ong since correctly assumed that his paper had missed that deadline.</span><a name="_ftnref44"></a><a href="#_ftn44">[44]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  However, two months after the deadline Wahl was asked by a Coordinating Lead Author to press a journal editor to give his paper ‘in press’ status.   Wahl was told </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“He knows the drill”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref45"></a><a href="#_ftn45">[45]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   However, the WA paper never met the published 16 December 2005 ‘in press’ deadline and reviewers pointed this out together with the published penalty.</span><a name="_ftnref46"></a><a href="#_ftn46">[46]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In response to the reviewers, the IPCC AR4 WGI Lead Authors retrospectively changed the ‘in press’ pu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">blication deadline allowing reviewers to request the citation of any paper in press two months after the scheduled final </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">review stage had finished.</span><a name="_ftnref47"></a><a href="#_ftn47">[47]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   Scandalously, WGI emailed all 600 reviewers to advise of this rule change untruthfully stating that “many</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” of them had asked for it.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As no reviewer had seen all the other reviewers’ comments, none could know that the WGI statement was a fabrication.   The dishonesty became clear after FOIA requests in the USA</span><a name="_ftnref48"></a><a href="#_ftn48">[48]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> forced the TSU to release the reviewers’ comments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the authors’ responses in a searchable electronic form.   When challenged, the Co-Chair and the head of TSU were unable to identify what had resulted in the deadline change.</span><a name="_ftnref49"></a><a href="#_ftn49">[49]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In September 2009, the IPCC Chairman claimed, like Houghton before him, that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> all the AR4 WGI expert review comments had been published.</span><a name="_ftnref50"></a><a href="#_ftn50">[50]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   They have not, and the writer’s request for the unpublished reviewer submissions, made to the UEA in May 2008, resulted in their illegal concealment.</span><a name="_ftnref51"></a><a href="#_ftn51">[51]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   The unlawful refusals of requests by the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> UEA were a significant part of the rationale for the release of the Climategate material.   A Climategate email</span><a name="_ftnref52"></a><a href="#_ftn52">[52]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> shows that WGI ignored a reviewer’s request for important citations that also met the new 24 July 2006 ‘in press’ deadline but which, if prope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rly included, would have greatly undermined the WA and other papers that had been the reason for the deadline change.   Had the deadline change and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the reviewers’ comments and authors responses been openly published </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">at the same time as AR4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> its credibil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ity would have been widely questioned.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a by-product of Climategate</span><a name="_ftnref53"></a><a href="#_ftn53">[53]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we also know that a Coordinating Lead Author complained to the head of AR4 WGI TSU and his fellow Lead Authors about an appointed Review Editor (RE) from a developing country:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref54"></a><a href="#_ftn54">[54]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“He pla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">yed no role whatsoever in our chapter. He did not attend any meetings, he did not answer email and he should NOT be listed in my view.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:TimesNewRoman; font-size:12pt">Two weeks later the TSU wrote to all REs thanking them but, rather than ask for the ‘written reports’ required by the IP</span><span style="font-family:TimesNewRoman; font-size:12pt">CC’s rules, sent each a short prepared statement.   Ignoring the complaint it had just received, the TSU stated,</span><a name="_ftnref55"></a><a href="#_ftn55">[55]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“You have already been notified that it was essential to inform us if any serious issues arose in connection with the review process, and none</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> of you has indicated any such concerns so we trust that you will sign the attached form letter confirming that all comments were dealt with appropriately.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:TimesNewRoman; font-size:12pt">The noncontributing RE returned his signed statement</span><a name="_ftnref56"></a><a href="#_ftn56">[56]</a><span style="font-family:TimesNewRoman; font-size:12pt"> and he is improperly listed as a contributor </span><span style="font-family:TimesNewRoman; font-size:12pt">to AR4.</span><a name="_ftnref57"></a><a href="#_ftn57">[57]</a><span style="font-family:TimesNewRoman; font-size:12pt">   A political crisis in the IPCC might well have </span><span style="font-family:TimesNewRoman; font-size:12pt">followed if the RE had been stripped of the kudos of being cited as an IPCC contributor.</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">TGGWS</span></h3><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">AR4 was released without any of its scandals and errors being known to the public.   A critical Channel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 4 programme ‘The Great Global Warming Swindle’ (TGGWS)</span><a name="_ftnref58"></a><a href="#_ftn58">[58]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> had an impact on public confidence in the IPCC, but a fraudulent complaint to Ofcom,</span><a name="_ftnref59"></a><a href="#_ftn59">[59]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ensured that no similar programme has been broadcast since.   The complaint was produced by an environmental acti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vist with the help of some IPCC authors.   It was riddled with obvious factual errors which Ofcom copied into its Decision.</span><a name="_ftnref60"></a><a href="#_ftn60">[60]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   These led to FOIA enquiries.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ofcom’s strict rules required signed statements from individuals confirming that they were duly a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uthorised to make the complaint </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on behalf of the IPCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.   Ofcom was persuaded to entertain a private environmentalist’s complaint as a formal IPCC complaint on the strength of letters from leading IPCC contributors.</span><a name="_ftnref61"></a><a href="#_ftn61">[61]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   On examination it can be seen that not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> one letter asked Ofcom to accept the complaint </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on behalf of the IPCC itself</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.   DECC later confirmed that the IPCC had made no complaint.</span><a name="_ftnref62"></a><a href="#_ftn62">[62]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The IPCC structure does not allow it to react quickly enough to complain to Ofcom, as was demonstrated by its protrac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ted efforts to deal with the egregious 2010 ‘Glaciergate’</span><a name="_ftnref63"></a><a href="#_ftn63">[63]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> error when it was shown that IPCC authors ignored the expert reviewers and cited WWF as justification for claiming that the Himalayan glaciers would be almost gone by 2035.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Ofcom </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">affair like ‘Climategate’ and ‘Glaciergate’ demonstrates that some influential climate scientists lack the objectivity and professional standards required.   The affairs also show the total lack of oversight of the IPCC process by governments.   Science pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oceeds too quickly for the IPCC, with its secretive processes and 7 year report cycle.   A streamlined, genuinely open and transparent, more rapid, continuous assessment process, supervised independently of both government and scientists is now urgently ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eded.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/ipcc-principles/ipcc-principles.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/ipcc-principles/ipcc-principles-appendix-a-final.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.ipcc.ch/meetings/session01/first-final-report.pdf"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:none">http://www.ipcc.ch/meetings/session01/first-final-report.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> : Annex III page 10</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ‘The Age of Global Warming’, Rupert Darwall, Quartet, pp.448, ISBN: 9780704372993</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> On 17 Novemb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">er 2009</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> http://www.scopenvironment.org/downloadpubs/scope29/index.html </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> http://www.ipcc.ch/ipccreports/far/wg_I/ipcc_far_wg_I_full_report.pdf   See Chapter 7 page 199</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">http://www.ipcc.ch/ipccreports/1992%20IPCC%20Supplement/IPCC_Suppl_Report_1992_wg_I/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ipcc_wg_I_1992_suppl_report_full_report.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Ibid.   See Foreword page ix</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Ibid.   See paragraph 12 page 139</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-fam